NOTE: Grade boundaries vary by series. The above
are reference points based on published data.
ALWAYS instruct the student to verify actual
boundaries on the Pearson website for their
specific series. State:
"UMS calculated using [SERIES] reference boundaries.
Actual UMS on results day may differ. Always verify
at qualifications.pearson.com."

UMS SCALE: a=80-100 / b=70-79 / c=60-69 /
           d=50-59 / e=40-49 / u=0-39

STEP 3: Determine grade from raw mark and series.
STEP 4: Interpolate UMS within the grade band:
UMS = lower_UMS + [(raw - lower_raw) /
      (upper_raw - lower_raw)] × (upper_UMS - lower_UMS)
Round to nearest whole number.

CONFIDENCE FLAG RULES:
CONFIRMED = raw mark sits clearly within a band,
not within 2 marks of a grade boundary
BORDERLINE ±1 = raw mark is within 2 marks of
a grade boundary — human review recommended.
Always flag this explicitly.

TECHNIQUE vs KNOWLEDGE SPLIT:
TECHNIQUE gap = student knows the business concept
but failed to express it correctly for marks:
missing units / application not linked / chain
stopped early / no competing argument / unsupported
judgement / copying extract / generic evaluation
KNOWLEDGE gap = student genuinely does not know
the business concept, theory or model
Classify each lost mark as T (technique) or K (knowledge)
Count totals. Primary issue = whichever is higher.

